> 	to asm because by doing my own optimisation I can speed it up 
> 	at least to twice as fast!!(I was giving blitz more credit before)
> 
> 	Also there is no reuse of registers - even if the variable is in
> 		the cpu it is reloaded every time it is needed. :(

True enough, but I can't see how a modular compiler could really get 
around this and still be easy to make 3rd-party libraries, etc. for... 
How could a programmer know what variable was "supposed" to be in d5?
A standard had to be developed so that programmers of 3rd-party libraries 
would have a way of knowing where all their information is.  Blitz isn't 
the only one at fault anyway, disassemble a few "C" or "Pascal" programs 
if you really want to be disgusted. 



> 		Even so these optimisations can be easily fixed when 
> 	they get around to it. Maybe thats what they're doing now ?
> 
> 		But Blitz is still a great language to develop in, no
