From relmore@silver.sdsmt.eduSun Sep  3 22:30:05 1995
Date: Mon, 10 Apr 1995 07:53:37 -0600 (MDT)
From: "Richard T. Elmore" <relmore@silver.sdsmt.edu>
To: Pink <D.C.J.Pink@herts.ac.uk>
Cc: The Blitz list <blitz-list@helsinki.fi>
Subject: RE: Files and array problem

On Mon, 10 Apr 1995, Pink wrote:

>   There isn`t a specific command to free an array, but arrays can be
> re-dimmed.  This means that you could re-dim (Just use the Dim command
> again with the same variable name) the array with a size of 0, which
> will automatically free the old array, and allocate 0 bytes for the new
> array.

I use this technique myself, but it doesn't actually allocate zero 
bytes-- remember element zero is still available and it takes up space.  
If you have an array of longs (4-bytes a piece) and dim n.l(0) the array 
would take up 4 bytes, plus the array header size (which I think is 8 or 
12 bytes.)

Still, it's the next-best-thing for not being able to ERASE an array!



