From relmore@silver.sdsmt.eduSun Sep  3 22:30:05 1995
Date: Tue, 11 Apr 1995 08:41:37 -0600 (MDT)
From: "Richard T. Elmore" <relmore@silver.sdsmt.edu>
To: Hesham Amiri <hmamiri@carbon.cudenver.edu>
Cc: Pink <D.C.J.Pink@herts.ac.uk>, The Blitz list <blitz-list@helsinki.fi>
Subject: Re: Finished Proggy

On Tue, 11 Apr 1995, Hesham Amiri wrote:

> BTW, can anybody tell me if there is a way to link c and Blitz code ?

There are a number of ways you could go about it-- depends I guess upon 
what you are doing... Are you talking about ".o" files or 
already-compiled executeables?  If you mean executeables, then here is a 
suggestion that will work in most cases, as long as your "C" program is 
only one HUNK:

Dig up a program called "BIN" I think it's on Aminet... The specific 
program I have was written by Bruno Costa in 1989...  Let's say we're 
trying to call a program originally called "cprog" from our blitz code.



-------------------------------------------------------------------------

<In CLI>
Bin cprog Blitz2:Includes/cprog.bin


<In Blitz2 Sourcecode>


;Your code here
NPrint "Just a test."


;Call the c-program...
JSR ?cprogbin

;End program
End


cprogbin:
INCBIN "Blitz2:Includes/cprog.bin"
Even




---------------------------------------------------------------------------

Passing parameters might be a bit more difficult, but try playing with 
placing a null-terminated string pointer in A0 before JSRing to the 
binary program... I believe you also should put the length of the string 
in D0.

The program's returncode (such as 20 for failure) will be returned in D0 
on exit.

Caution: If the program supplies it's own WBStartup code, then you'll 
probably have a crash if you provide it yourself for the Blitz program.

This is a clumsy way to do things, but it works, and is easier to explain 
than trying to get ".o" files to work.





	+---------------------------------------------------------------+
	|      Richard T. Elmore   -   "Head" of HeadSoft Software      |
	| E-MAIL: relmore@silver.sdsmt.edu          TEL: (605) 348-3337 |     
