From oz@ozzy.demon.co.ukSun Sep  3 22:30:06 1995
Date: Wed, 12 Apr 95 18:43:37 GMT
From: Brian Skreeg <oz@ozzy.demon.co.uk>
To: blitz-list@helsinki.fi
Subject: Wanted. 1 maths speedup!

	Thanks to all who helped with my ignorance of Blitz's Tan function.
I've got it all working fine and I've included a small bit below. Can
anyone see a way to speed it up as it's running far to slow? Is there a way
to use my fpu? I know I could use tables but I'm not sure how. If someone
suggs tables can they tell me how? I'll need a table for 720 divisions in a
circle.

db=0                    ; double buffer
column=0                ; column no.
xp=1664 : yp=2344       ; player coords
xi=0 : yi=0             ; intercepts to find
ray_ang=10              ; angle/column
x_dist=20 : y_dist=0     ; relative offsets , distance to wall.

.mainloop
While RawStatus($45)=0
  Show db : db=1-db
  Use BitMap db
  Cls 0
  BitMapOutput db : Locate 0,0
  Repeat
    Gosub raycast
    Gosub draw
    column+1
    ray_ang+0.5
  Until column=128
  column=0 : ray_ang=10 : ray_num=127
  If RawStatus($21)<>0 Then xp-32 : ray_ang+1  ; only moving 2 dirs at mo
  If RawStatus($20)<>0 Then yp-32 : ray_ang-1
  VWait
Wend
End

;---------------Ray-casting--------------

.raycast
  Gosub horizontal
  x_dist=Sqr(((yp-yi)^2)+((xp-xi)^2))
  Gosub vertical
  y_dist=Sqr(((xp-xi)^2)+((yp-yi)^2))
Return

.horizontal
  yi=Int(yp/64)*64

.trhcast
  xi=xp-(Tan((ray_ang*Pi/180))*(yp-yi))
  If xi<0Then Return
  gx=(xi/64) : gy=(yi/64)
  If grid(gx,gy)<>0 Then Return
  yi-64
  Goto trhcast

.vertical
  xi=Int(xp/64)*64

.trvcast
  v_ang=90-ray_ang
  yi=yp-(1/Tan(ray_ang*Pi/180)*(xp-xi))
  If yi<0 Then Return
  gx=(xi/64) : gy=(yi/64)
  If grid(gx,gy)<>0 Then Return
  xi-64
  count+1
  Goto trvcast

; ------------calc n draw-------

.draw

Simple line drawing based on how far. Planning to depth shade or poss
asm scaling. :) as if I could.


;---------Binary Includes---------------

INCDIR "maps/"
grid: IncBin grid1

Wot you think?

Will tables speed it up that much? Or am I banging me `ed of the wallpaper?


 |-Brian Skreeg-----------------------|
 |-Lead Guitarist and PR Silly person-|
 |-Show me a cake and I'll eat it-----|


From brettc@spaz.manawatu.planet.co.nzSun Sep  3 22:30:06 1995
Date: Thu, 13 Apr 95 20:08:01 +1300
From: Brett Cooper <brettc@spaz.manawatu.planet.co.nz>
To: blitz-list@helsinki.fi
Subject: Re: Finished Proggy

> On Tue, 11 Apr 1995, Hesham Amiri wrote:
> 
> > BTW, can anybody tell me if there is a way to link c and Blitz code ?
> 
> There are a number of ways you could go about it-- depends I guess upon 
> what you are doing... Are you talking about ".o" files or 
> already-compiled executeables?  If you mean executeables, then here is a 
> suggestion that will work in most cases, as long as your "C" program is 
> only one HUNK:

[ Excelent advice from Richard snipped out ]

To link c (object) code into blitz,  well I have had this idea for 
includeing it into blitz code.  Some say it may not work but it's 
only a bit of a cludge but it kind a does what I wanted it for.

And I have not put the defines in but they have there correct names :)
if you want to use this for anything at all.  Know rules in useing it.

;  the huge source below.  Includes a cheap hunk relocation for objects.

*obj=?object                  ; a pointer to the incbin of the code.obj

If Peek.l(*obj) = #HUNK_UNIT
  *obj+4                      ; point to hunk size
  nl.l=(Peek.l(*obj)*4)       ; size of hunk unit name
  *obj+nl+4                   ; find next HUNK

  *obj+4                      ; point to hunk size
  nl.l=(Peek.l(*obj)*4)       ; size of hunk name
  *obj+nl+4                   ; find next HUNK

  *obj+4                      ; point to hunk size
  nl.l=(Peek.l(*obj)*4)       ; get size of code hunk
  *START=*obj+4               ; rember where code hunk was
  *obj+nl+4                   ; find next HUNK

  *obj+4                      ; point to number of relocations to do
  RELO.l = Peek.l(*obj)       ; numer of relocations to do

  *obj+8                      ; skip which start hunk coz WE know!

  For sh = 0 To (RELO*4)-4 Step 4           ; relocation offsets
    cv.l = *START                           ; Base Address of CRUNCHER
    cv.l + Peek.l(*START+(Peek.l(*obj+sh))) ; add relocation value
    Poke.l *START+(Peek.l(*obj+sh)),cv      ; modify CRUNCH code
  Next
EndIf

;-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
; The object code I was playing with was a cruncher.  Written by a friend .
; Or it was some peace of code like a cruncher with a real loctaion table :)
;-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

input.l  = ?dead    ; not used at pressent
output.l = $4e000   ; output of decrunched file	<-  hell who wrote this :)

*t=?cd		    ; Look look I even pass prometers to the object code.
Poke.l  *t,input
Poke.l  *t+4,output

GetReg  d1,*t       ; pass out put value
Call    *START      ; call object code
JSR     $4e000      ; - bang that hard address -

End

cd:  Dc.l  0,0

object:	IncBin  "crun/decrunch41.o"
Even
dead:	IncBin  "crun/t.cru"		;  why did I put this hear?

;------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Eye Hope that someone finds this bit of blitz useful and very fastenateing :)
This would be cool to implement as a standard instruction within blitz but
as I know very little about such things.  But I try real hard to get my point
out into the publick arena.

Ranting has stopped.

Brett
brettc@spaz.manawatu.planet.nz  (Brett Cooper)
