From mcc@meteorology.edinburgh.ac.ukSun Sep  3 22:30:06 1995
Date: Thu, 13 Apr 95 10:37:56 BST
From: M Cooper <mcc@meteorology.edinburgh.ac.uk>
To: blitz-list@helsinki.fi
Subject: re: Maths Speedup

Brian:

Use a look-up table, it will really speed things up.
All you have to do is dim an array with 719 elements, and store the
tangent for that angle in each element

e.g

Dim tn.q(719)
for i=0 to 719
tn(i)=tan(i*2*pi/720)
next

or maybe in your case tn=1/tan((i*2*pi/720).
This way the expensive maths stuff (calculating the tan's) is removed
from the main loop of your ray-caster. The speed difference will be
amazing.
Also, I presume you're using .q variables (and if not, then do so). You
can replace all occurrences of /64 with ASR 6 if this is the case- that
will also speed things up as the binarty shifters are much quicker than
dividing. 
Possibly the distance calculation can be speeded up. 
I think that 

dy=yp-yi:dx=xp-xi:xdist=sqr(dy*dy+dx*dx)

would be faster than using powers, and it may be possible to approximate
the sqr somehow with look-up tables if you sacrifice a bit of accuracy,
I'm not too sure.

Basically, try to avoid using maths calls such as sqr, tan etc.
explicitly in your loops, these will bog it down something chronic.

Hope this helps

Mike Cooper





