From sis3149@sis.port.ac.ukSun Sep  3 22:30:07 1995
Date: Thu, 27 Apr 1995 11:06:33 +0100 (BST)
From: Stephen McNamara <sis3149@sis.port.ac.uk>
To: Brett Johansen <c9108939@sol.newcastle.edu.au>
Cc: blitz-list@helsinki.fi
Subject: Re: proc calls

On Thu, 27 Apr 1995, Brett Johansen wrote:

> 		Say I have a asm procedure
> 		myproc{a.w,addrtable.l}
> 
> 			move d1,a0
> 			move (a0),d1	;just get data
> 			.
> 			.
> 			.
> 			;now I want to call Blit x,y,0
> 			;if I have the vars in the regs d0,d1,d2
> 			;already, can I then JSR blitsubroutine
> 			;to save blitz reloading them?

Not quite that easy.  There is the TokeJsr function but I don't know if 
this will require you to directly specify shape to blit.  Also you'd have 
to set up a3 (I think) to point to the Addr Bitmap of the currently used 
bitmap.

> 			;If so how do I find the addr of  blitsubroutine
> 			; to jump to.
> 			.
> 			.
> 			do some more asm;
> 			asmexit
> 		end statement

My suggestion: but this inside a blitz command library.

> 	Also when a blit command is started does the CPU keep executing 
> 		when the blitter is drawing?

Blit does such bitplane of the blit separately, so the cpu is waiting for 
the blit to finish after every frame BUT the last one.
 
> 		And so if you put commands after a blit you get them done
> 		for "free" , until the blit you hit another blit command
> 		before the drawing is fininshed and the program flow has
> 		to wait?

Not quite - read the bitplane thing above.
 			
> 	and finally I just discovered you can put #SIZE in Dc.w if you
> 		place it inside {}
 
> 	ie dc.w	12,5,{#SIZE\3},6,7.....

Yep.


Steve Mc.

