From relmore@silver.sdsmt.eduSun Sep  3 22:30:08 1995
Date: Tue, 2 May 1995 10:00:32 -0600 (MDT)
From: "Richard T. Elmore" <relmore@silver.sdsmt.edu>
To: MACIEJ GORNY <GORN4907@mars.rowan.edu>
Cc: blitz-list@helsinki.fi
Subject: Re: Q: Using AvailMem_

On Mon, 1 May 1995, MACIEJ GORNY wrote:

> Date: Mon, 1 May 1995 15:03:13 EST
> From: MACIEJ GORNY <GORN4907@mars.rowan.edu>
> To: blitz-list@helsinki.fi
> Subject: Q: Using AvailMem_
> 
> Does anybody know what are the parameters that AvailMem_ needs to 
> show the available memory? is there anyway to check seperately how 
> much fast and how much chip RAM is left?

There are some definitions in Amigalibs.Res that would make the flags 
easier to deal with.  You can "OR" them together for combinations as well.

Here they are with a brief example:

#MEMF_ANY=0   		;Any type of memory will do
#MEMF_PUBLIC=1
#MEMF_CHIP=2
#MEMF_FAST=4
#MEMF_LOCAL=256 	;Memory that doesn't go away at RESET
#MEMF_24BITDMA=512 	;DMAable memory within 24 bits of address
#MEMF_KICK=1024 	;Memory that can be used for KickTags
#MEMF_LARGEST=131072  	;Return largest chunk size
#MEMF_TOTAL=524288	;Return total size of memory


;Return all FAST RAM in system:

size.l=AvailMem_(#MEMF_FAST|#MEMF_TOTAL)





Hope this helps!
	+---------------------------------------------------------------+
	|      Richard T. Elmore   -   "Head" of HeadSoft Software      |
	| E-MAIL: relmore@silver.sdsmt.edu          TEL: (605) 348-3337 |     
	+---------------------------------------------------------------+



From relmore@silver.sdsmt.eduSun Sep  3 22:30:08 1995
Date: Tue, 2 May 1995 10:26:26 -0600 (MDT)
From: "Richard T. Elmore" <relmore@silver.sdsmt.edu>
To: Colin Saunders <colin@ahl.co.uk>
Cc: Blitz-list@helsinki.fi
Subject: Re: Memory...

On Tue, 2 May 1995, Colin Saunders wrote:

> I know there are "two" types of memory in the Amiga - chip and fast -
> but thats about all I now about memory...

Well, there are actually types other than these two, but for most 
practical purposes, you can say memory is either "CHIP" accessable memory 
or NOT "CHIP" accessable memory.

 
> A few questions:
> 
> 1.  What is the difference between chip and fast memory?

The only real important difference is CHIP memory is memory that falls 
within the addressable range of the Amiga's custom chips, which means 
only this memory can be accessed for either sound or graphics etc. that 
use custom chips.


> 2.  What implications does this have on games?

One common example is you end up with insufficient memory for all your 
games bitmaps, shapes, sound etc. even though you have 16M of fast memory 
available.  You're limited to the amount of CHIP ram you have for just
about all your graphics, sound etc. unless you're using a graphics card 
like the Picasso-II, which can use FAST ram for it's graphics.

> 3.  What control does Blitz provide for placing data (or code) in a
>     certain type of memory?

UNFORTUNEATELY, there is no control... For now you can't know where any 
code or data will end up when it's loaded.... The only safe thing to do 
is allocate the specific type you need (such as CHIP) and copy data from 
the address of your program's data to this allocated CHIP ram.  It's a 
horrible waste, but until this problem is fixed, we're stuck.


> 4.  What are the implications of different machines having different
>     amounts of the two types of memory?

AGA and ECS machines that have more CHIP memory can use more graphics and 
sound in games than the older, obsolete machines.  With an A1200, for 
example, you have 2 full megabytes of memory for your game's images, 
sound, music etc.  On some machines this is only 512K or even 256K.


Keep in touch!

	+---------------------------------------------------------------+
	|      Richard T. Elmore   -   "Head" of HeadSoft Software      |
	| E-MAIL: relmore@silver.sdsmt.edu          TEL: (605) 348-3337 |     
	+---------------------------------------------------------------+



