From sueec@westminster.ac.ukSun Sep  3 22:30:09 1995
Date: Sun, 7 May 1995 16:16:56 +0100 (BST)
From: Ricky Clarke <sueec@westminster.ac.uk>
To: blitz-list@helsinki.fi
Subject: Just a few quickies...


  ( NOTE: This message has been sent before but I'm not sure whether it actually got through or not... So here goes again...)

  Hello all!

  Can anybody help me with any of the following please?


  Query #1:

   I have written an intuition program which uses GTLists quite a lot.
 I was wondering if anybody out there knows of, or would be interested in
 engineering, an implementation of the 'GTListHit' command below...

  ; Code starts here. Don't try to execute/run it - IT WON'T WORK ;)

    Select WaitEvent        ;Wait for an IDCMPEvent to occur
    Case #GadgetUpEvent     ;A gadget has been released
      Select GTListHit
      Case 0
        Select GadgetHit
        Case 0
        Case 1
        End Select
      Case 1
        Select GadgetHit
        Case 0
        Case 1
        End Select
      End Select
    End Select

  ; Code ends

   As you can see from the above, I would like 'GTListHit' to return/hold the
 GTList object number that the selected GTGadget exists within. I know this
 is probably rather wordy and not particularly well explained... Sorry :)


  Query #2:

   In the program I mentioned above I've been developing my own GTList
 scaling routines. Using the 'DetachGTList', 'GTFreeGadget' and 'Free GTList'
 command combination I've been deallocating GTLists and then reallocating
 them at a different size. It seems, bowever, that the GTLists that I've
 finished with and have (supposedly) got rid of (i.e. No longer take up
 memory) are NOT actually being cleared from memory until the program finally
 terminates. I don't think this is the fault of either of the first two
 commands memtioned, however, I'm not sure...
   I really do need some help with with this as a constant memory drain every
 time a GTList is reattached makes my program completely usless (Seeing as
 that is, in effect, its purpose :) )


  Query #3:

   Did anything ever come of the 'IconToShape' command that I asked about a
 while back (esp. RI-Group and Elmore)? I'm still interested in using such a
 command.


  Thanks for bothering to read this request (And for any help)...

    Ricky Clarke (EMail: sueec@westminster.ac.uk or sueec@wmin.ac.uk)


From relmore@silver.sdsmt.eduSun Sep  3 22:30:09 1995
Date: Sun, 7 May 1995 10:53:31 -0600 (MDT)
From: "Richard T. Elmore" <relmore@silver.sdsmt.edu>
To: Greg Siklos <gsiklos@phantom.com>
Cc: blitz-list@helsinki.fi
Subject: Re: wbwidth & wbheight

On Sun, 7 May 1995, Greg Siklos wrote:

> 	I,ve just run into a weird problem concerning wbwidth & wbheight. For
> some reason they are suddenly returning the wrong sizes for my workbench 
> screens for example my wbench is set for 676 width and 467 height and WBwidth
> returns 640 &WBheight returns 400. I haven't ever had any sort of problem 

WBWidth, WBHeight and WBViewmode functions are all buggy when it comes to 
screen types unavailable prior to 2.0 or 3.0, or with widths beyond 640 
and heights beyond 512.  I wrote a library some time ago to address this  
problem by providing the true values for ANY screen you open or 
"FindScreen."  (Including WBToScreen x)  If you're interested, please 
contact me.

	+---------------------------------------------------------------+
	|      Richard T. Elmore   -   "Head" of HeadSoft Software      |
	| E-MAIL: relmore@silver.sdsmt.edu          TEL: (605) 348-3337 |     
	+---------------------------------------------------------------+



From josh@pinsight.comSun Sep  3 22:30:09 1995
Date: Sun, 7 May 1995 11:58:34 -0700 (PDT)
From: Josh Farley <josh@pinsight.com>
To: Greg Siklos <gsiklos@phantom.com>
Cc: blitz-list@helsinki.fi
Subject: Re: wbwidth & wbheight



On Sun, 7 May 1995, Greg Siklos wrote:

> 	I,ve just run into a weird problem concerning wbwidth & wbheight. For
> some reason they are suddenly returning the wrong sizes for my workbench 
> screens for example my wbench is set for 676 width and 467 height and WBwidth
> returns 640 &WBheight returns 400. I haven't ever had any sort of problem 

  I had the same problem... Blitz's commands will only return the default 
values... to get the "real" values, do the following:

WBToScreen 0
*s0.Screen=peek.l(addr screen(0))
wx=*s0\Width
wy=*s0\Height


  This should work...

