From sis3149@sis.port.ac.ukSun Sep  3 22:30:10 1995
Date: Tue, 9 May 1995 09:34:02 +0100 (BST)
From: Stephen McNamara <sis3149@sis.port.ac.uk>
To: Ricky Clarke <sueec@westminster.ac.uk>
Cc: blitz-list@helsinki.fi
Subject: Re: Just a few quickies...

On Sun, 7 May 1995, Ricky Clarke wrote:

>   Query #1:
> 
>    I have written an intuition program which uses GTLists quite a lot.
>  I was wondering if anybody out there knows of, or would be interested in
>  engineering, an implementation of the 'GTListHit' command below...
> 
>   ; Code starts here. Don't try to execute/run it - IT WON'T WORK ;)

[Code deleted]

>    As you can see from the above, I would like 'GTListHit' to return/hold the
>  GTList object number that the selected GTGadget exists within. I know this
>  is probably rather wordy and not particularly well explained... Sorry :)

You don't really need a command like this, just have unique gadget IDs 
between the lists.  For example, for gadgets on gtlist 0 have IDs 
counting from 100, for gtlist 1 have IDs counting from 200 etc.

Not sure how easy/hard it'd be to implement the GTListHit command.  It'd 
certainly be a little tricky since the same gadget IDs can exist in 
different GTLists.

>   Query #2:
> 
>    In the program I mentioned above I've been developing my own GTList
>  scaling routines. Using the 'DetachGTList', 'GTFreeGadget' and 'Free GTList'
>  command combination I've been deallocating GTLists and then reallocating
>  them at a different size. It seems, bowever, that the GTLists that I've
>  finished with and have (supposedly) got rid of (i.e. No longer take up
>  memory) are NOT actually being cleared from memory until the program finally
>  terminates. I don't think this is the fault of either of the first two
>  commands memtioned, however, I'm not sure...
>    I really do need some help with with this as a constant memory drain every
>  time a GTList is reattached makes my program completely usless (Seeing as
>  that is, in effect, its purpose :) )

There shouldn't be any mem drain in you're using the latest update to the 
GT library that I released.  I'm pretty certain that I found every case 
that was chewing memory - I tested several programs with MemMeter and did 
loads of attaching/detaching/freeing etc without any drain.  Maybe this 
is another OS problem - since I am only able to test on OS3.0 I cannot be 
entirely sure that the code is working okay, although there is no obvious 
reason as to why it wouldn't be working.

>   Query #3:
> 
>    Did anything ever come of the 'IconToShape' command that I asked about a
>  while back (esp. RI-Group and Elmore)? I'm still interested in using such a
>  command.

Errrmmmm..... well I meant to get around to it - just been too busy :)
Sorry, try and do it soon....


Steve Mc.

