From josh@ecst.csuchico.eduSun Sep  3 22:30:10 1995
Date: Wed, 10 May 1995 21:36:39 -0700 (PDT)
From: josh farley <josh@ecst.csuchico.edu>
To: The Crow <tjstone@netshop.net>
Cc: MO Tiffany <cca93057@sun1.bham.ac.uk>, blitz-list@helsinki.fi
Subject: Re: Scroll example/off topic



On Wed, 10 May 1995, The Crow wrote:

>     Should one be able to write a commercial quality game in Blitz Basic
>     without having to resort to writing your own assembler routines or using
>     "advanced" techniques (such as cludges, etc. which seem to come up from
>     time to time in blitz-list conversations)??

  Yes.

  Oh, want more detail? :)

  I have found it to be very easy to program high-quality programs in 
blitz, without using hardware hacks, or even using Blitz-mode.  My 
programs all multi-task, run on 24-bit boards, and don't use hacks...

  Sometimes assembly is useful to gain speed, other times it's 
unnecessarry if you're creative... For the most part, using a combination 
of blitz commands and OS-calls seems to work fine for me... then again, 
I'm not all that interested in getting 60 fps... I can live with less, if 
I gain better gameplay, and more colors on screen...

