From relmore@silver.sdsmt.eduSun Sep  3 22:30:11 1995
Date: Thu, 11 May 1995 08:02:36 -0600 (MDT)
From: "Richard T. Elmore" <relmore@silver.sdsmt.edu>
To: The Crow <tjstone@netshop.net>
Cc: MO Tiffany <cca93057@sun1.bham.ac.uk>, blitz-list@helsinki.fi
Subject: Re: Scroll example/off topic


On Wed, 10 May 1995, The Crow wrote:

>     Should one be able to write a commercial quality game in Blitz Basic
>     without having to resort to writing your own assembler routines or using
>     "advanced" techniques (such as cludges, etc. which seem to come up from
>     time to time in blitz-list conversations)??

I think so, definitely.  Although help from assembly routines or calling 
OS routines can be a big help for special requirements in a program, 
Blitz still has enough potential on it's own to write a lot of good 
software, including games.  

If you download 3rd-party libaries, you'll also notice that many of them 
provide an easier interface to features that were only available before 
with assembly and/or loads of OS calls...  But, beware:  Not all the 
3rd-party libraries out there are good ones, so just experiment and see 
which combination of standard Blitz and 3rd-party libraries help you 
achieve your programming goals with the least difficulty.  

If all else fails, you could probably achieve with standard OS calls many 
of those things Blitz doesn't offer on it's own.  They're a bit rugged to 
figure out, but it's worth it to make yourself as familiar with the 
operating system as you can.


	+---------------------------------------------------------------+
	|      Richard T. Elmore   -   "Head" of HeadSoft Software      |
	| E-MAIL: relmore@silver.sdsmt.edu          TEL: (605) 348-3337 |     
	+---------------------------------------------------------------+



