From sis3149@sis.port.ac.ukSun Sep  3 22:30:11 1995
Date: Fri, 12 May 1995 08:54:15 +0100 (BST)
From: Stephen McNamara <sis3149@sis.port.ac.uk>
To: Blitzlist <blitz-list@helsinki.fi>
Subject: Blitz Bug Or My Bug? You tell me...

Lets have a little story shall we...  Lets say a person wrote a nice 
debugger, and everything went very well.  The program worked and was 
actually quite useful.  Now lets say that the aforementioned person wrote 
a nice little menus library that took advantage of Gadtools to give nice 
layouts etc.  Now lets also say that he had a thought : 'why not make 
my nice little debugger use that little menu library I wrote?'.  This 
thought sounded nice so he decided to go ahead with putting in his 
library........

-=-=-=-=-=-=--=-=-=-=-=-=--=-=-=-=-=-=-=--==--=

That was yesterday.  I put in the library and everything went well, until 
I tried to STOP a program using the debugger.  Amazingly nothing 
happened.  The program being debugged doesn't even respond to CTRL-ALT-C 
or the STOP command placed in its source code.  Just the simple presence 
of the menu library in the debugger executable stops it working 
completely.  I don't even have to execute a command from the library to 
stop the debugger working....

I really don't understand this.  The library does nothing special, its 
init and finit routines just open the GadTools.library - I've even tried 
disabling this code but the problem persists.

Let me just clarify this problem slightly by saying if the debugger 
doesn't use my library AT ALL it CAN STOP a program that itself uses the 
library.

Is this some strange bug in the Blitz Compiler I wonder?  Or is it my 
being really stupid?  Because for the life of me I can't work out whats 
going on.....  


Any suggestions would be appreciated.


Confused,
Steve Mc.

