From relmore@silver.sdsmt.eduSun Sep  3 22:30:11 1995
Date: Fri, 12 May 1995 12:19:24 -0600 (MDT)
From: "Richard T. Elmore" <relmore@silver.sdsmt.edu>
To: Andy Pelton <apelton@coventry.ac.uk>
Cc: Blitzs-List <blitz-list@helsinki.fi>
Subject: Re: What is ABC

> What the hell is This ABC thingy (apart from the obvious!).

>From what I gather, the new update from Blitz2 (tentatively called ABC) 
will not only be a complete overhaul of the Blitz we know and love(?) but 
it will be able to cross-compile for different machines, such as the Sega 
Genesis, Atari Jaguar, maybe even PC or MAC...  Hope it's as good as it 
sounds!

> Also How do you use the Display copper effects such as DisplayRainbow
> as everytime i use them an not enough room error appears.

>From the sketchy docs in Bums 5-7, I've figured out *this* much, though I 
wish I knew some more myself:

In your InitCopList command, you must specify a negative amount for the 
copper room... If you're doing an ECS rainbow that only affects one 
register (like color #0) this would be -1.  For AGA, it would be -4.

Then set up your palette and try the DisplayRainbow command.  BTW, if 
you're trying to use it with the PaletteRange command, I've had no 
success with that.  It seems PaletteRange is broken for the time being.
 

	+---------------------------------------------------------------+
	|      Richard T. Elmore   -   "Head" of HeadSoft Software      |
	| E-MAIL: relmore@silver.sdsmt.edu          TEL: (605) 348-3337 |     
	+---------------------------------------------------------------+



From relmore@silver.sdsmt.eduSun Sep  3 22:30:11 1995
Date: Fri, 12 May 1995 12:23:30 -0600 (MDT)
From: "Richard T. Elmore" <relmore@silver.sdsmt.edu>
To: Pink <D.C.J.Pink@herts.ac.uk>
Cc: The Blitz list <blitz-list@helsinki.fi>
Subject: Re: Screen Bitmaps

On Fri, 12 May 1995, Pink wrote:

> Is there anyway to know this size in advance without actually creating 
> the screen, getting the ScreensBitmap and then Peek ing the XClip value?

I might be wrong, but I *think* it is the size of the screen to the 
nearest 16-pixel boundry (rounded up.)  That means if you have a screen 
300 pixels wide, you'll need a bitmap 320 pixels wide...


