From acid@iconz.co.nzSun Sep  3 22:30:12 1995
Date: Thu, 18 May 1995 22:54:03 +1200 (NZST)
From: Simon <acid@iconz.co.nz>
To: Stephen McNamara <sis3149@sis.port.ac.uk>
Cc: blitz-list@helsinki.fi
Subject: Re: Am I moaning? Or being reasonable? 



On Thu, 18 May 1995, Stephen McNamara wrote:

> Is this Super NES code?  I'm sure thats got an 8 bit chip like the Z80.
> 
> How about getting back to the amy for a few weeks? ;-)
> 
> 
No its the coprocessor on the megadrive running at 4mhz with some very 
slow opcodes indeed, makes the 68000K at 7 look like a ferrari.

As for Ami, I've been working on an editor (haven't we all!) which lets 
you design 3D shapes with a number of bizarre tools, god it is so hard 
making things good enough for your average graphics person say what...

Anyway, once you design your lego-3d style shape you can paint on it like 
dpaint so edges can have darker blocks which makes the shape look rounder 
(see harddrivin usa for best example of this technique)).

Anyway, each block is one pixel and the z80 and 68000 are both going to 
be rendering cars on the fly by a sort of recursive line drawing system, 
and seeing as megadrive is nibble per pixel it is a bit quick than old 
ami's bitplanes.

The code is then going onto the gpu of the jaguar, this baby runs at 
28mhz, is risk meaning properly written machine code = 1 instruction per 
cycle. A lo res pixel takes 140 ns, so with a slightly smaller display 
I think we can get somthing like 28mil/320*200*50 gives you something 
like 10 instructions for each pixel at 50 fps.

A fast PC is going to give better performance but unless you have a 
stealth or similar graphics card it takes the best part a frame just to 
transfer graphics into VGA. So PC sucks.

Anyway, back to Jaguar, the DSP is just as fast as GPU so you can 
pre-process your data before it gets to the GPU. For us this means that 
the mountains and shit we have in our new iso-killer can be converted 
from curves (nurby ones at that) into a dense array of triangles which 
the gpu can then merrily draw (1200 per frame at present).

Hmmm, now i think ID have cottoned on to the jag because it is getting 
their next release first with PC so that should be cool. Also street 
price is now less than 150 quid which to me is just awesome.

OK, Amiga is not dead but Ted does deserve to be shot. I will be 
releasing latest source code to Ted in Bum8 and I will have some time 
next week to get it finished.

Sorry for the technical shit but if you get a cable with ABC that lets 
you plug into 60 mips of power for 150 quid I think some of you will 
appreciate this.

I'm off to netscape...

Bye.


