I could give it a go, but my Amiga`s still not quite sorted (what with a
new HD just gone in there...), so I would say Id knock a little something up
this weekend, but....

Lets see what Nigel comes up with anyway..... (see his earlier mail)

> opinions for making it even better. Taking the discussion rigth
> away to c.s.a.programmer could be good - but making a good example
> first and then referring to it could be even better.

Tis what I thought.  ;}

> I have also dreamed a little bit of something else concerning
> help for applications: some kind of "living" mascots which
> would give the help. That could be nice for at least kids and
> beginners... but let's look at that later (if someone with
> animation skills is interested, that is).

This could be implemnted as an option.  So that the user could select Help,
and depending on their 'user-rating', then the help comes as either just
a simple few words to describe things, or that plus words, or with a little
'mascot'  The latter is not necessary and doesnt need to be supported by
all, but would consist of some basic anims for the character that could
be put together.  I think this is definitely an extra for 'after'.

I was thinking of something like this...

	.-------------------------.
	|I|_______________________|   <--- Here goes the short desc.
	|                         |
	|                         |
	|                         |   <--- Here goes a longer desc.
	|                         |
	'-------------------------'

Just the window title could be shown for the simplest version of help
with an expand gadget to get the rest out.

As for what Nigel said about implementation..

>	 It would be easy to write a helplib but the issue is how it would 
>work. I think it would be an idea have the following commands,
>
>	InitHelp UseWindow#,MaxWidth,Clearwhenempty
>
>	DisplayHelp helptext$

Something like this is what I had in mind, although commands more like..

InitHelp UseWindow#,x,y,w,h   <-- sets up help stuff 'forever'
ClearWhenEmpty On|Off         <-- a flag so it could be turned on/off as needed
OpenHelp                      <-- open the help window
CloseHelp                     <-- close the help window
CurrentHelp simple$,helptext$ <-- (instead of DisplayHelp)

	A markup language would help, but we only need a few things, such as
bold and underline.  Obviously not neede for simple$ (this is what goes in
the window title).

Thats about all i can think to contribute for now.  

Mark Tiffany

